Diagnosis. Males 25.9–53.9 mm long, 1.8–3.2 mm high, ( 44 + 2 +T)–( 52 + 1 +T) segments, adult males varied between the developmental stadia X–XII. Overall body colour greyish black with a longitudinal black line dorsally. Ozopores on the suture, form of preanal process variable, sometimes straight but mostly curved dorsally. Male genitalia (
Fig. 1
): promeres (
Fig. 2
) with special riffle for holding opisthomere; apical end of promere with a serrated lobe; opisthomere (
Figs. 3–7
) with two well-pronounced processes, both well-developed, serrated and directed ventrally (parallel with the telopodite). Telopodite with two processes, a side lobe and a dermal lobe ending in a flagellal hook.

Remarks. Following
Verhoeff (e.g. 1907 )
the anterior process of the opisthomere was frequently called “Schutzblattfortsatz” while the posterior one “Mesomeritfortsatz” but its position clearly shows that it is not a part of the mesomere (
Attems 1927
). In this genus, according to Attems’ ( 1927 ) nomenclature, the mesomere is a paracoxite or coxal process (
Attems 1940
) and it is similar to the “Schutzblattfortsatz”. There is a telopodite situated apically on the opisthomere, with two processes: anterior called “Nebenlappen” i.e. side lobe, and posterior “Hautlappen, welches sich an das Flagellumhäckchen anschließt” (
Verhoeff 1907
) i.e. “dermal lobe”, ending in a flagellal hook.
